\begin_layout Section
Finitely Repeated Games
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Normally, exposition of finitely repeated games use the Prisoners' Dilemma
 and the equilibrium concept is SPNE.
 However, let me introduce the following Proposition which applies to all
 repeated games:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
If the stage game 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(I,\Sigma,\vec{u})$
\end_inset

 has a unique NE, then the finitely repeated game of this stage game, with
 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left\{ 1,...,T\right\} $
\end_inset

 has a unique subgame perfect outcome: the NE of the stage game is played
 in every stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is that this isn't very interesting.
 What about non-NE play at some of the stage games in a finitely repeated
 game? For example, for a given SPNE, could we have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cooperate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in some of the stage games of such SPNE of the finitely repeated Prisoners'
 Dilemma? 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a 2 period Prisoners' Dilemma, we won't be able to sustain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cooperate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as an SPNE, regardless of the payoffs.
 Can you think of a reason? HINT: It has to do with credibility in the final
 stage game.
 On the other hand, in an infinitely repeated Prisoners' Dilemma, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cooperate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be sustained in equilibrium despite the fact that the only NE of the
 stage game is [Defect, Defect].
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I'm not going to go into this in the section notes, but I refer you to Gibbons
 (1992, Section 2.3A).
 The take-away is that if there exists a credible threat or promise about
 future behavior (in the form of punishments which are NE in the stage game),
 then current behavior can be influenced.
 This means that a cooperative outcome can be achieved in certain finitely
 repeated games (even in games with 2 periods).
 
\end_layout

