\begin_layout Subsection
The Grim Trigger Strategy
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Only for those interested.
 For those not interested, just remember that in an infinitely repeated
 game, you'll be able to find a grim trigger strategy which is SPNE.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do we care so much about Grim Trigger strategies? The reason is that
 they always exist in dynamic or repeated games.
 Consider the following theorem (the proof of which can be found in Fudenberg
 and Tirole):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{*}\in S$
\end_inset

 is a pure strategy SPNE, with the distribution of on the equilibrium path
 actions given by 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a|\sigma^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Then, there exists a discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\delta}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>\bar{\delta}$
\end_inset

, there exists a SPNE 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{**}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(a|\sigma^{*})=p(a|\sigma^{**})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{**}$
\end_inset

 involves a continuation payoff of 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}^{minmax}(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}^{*})$
\end_inset

 to player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is the first to deviate from 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{**}$
\end_inset

 at date t after some history 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{t-1}\in H^{t-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
U_{i}^{minmax}(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}^{*})=\min_{\sigma_{-i}^{*}\in S_{-i}}\max_{\sigma_{i}\in S_{i}}\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\delta^{s}u_{i}(\sigma_{i,t+s},\sigma_{-i,t+s}^{*}).\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In short, if there exists a SPNE in an infinitely repeated game, then for
 a high enough discount factor, there exists a strategy profile where the
 first player to deviate receives her minmax continuation payoff which is
 also SPNE.
 Note that it could be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{*}=\sigma^{**}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is why we look at Grim Trigger Strategies.
 Note that the theorem above was written for a general dynamic model.
 It can be simplified for purposes of the infinitely repeated game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Recursive Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no way to provide you with a thorough review of recursive methods
 and Bellman equations, however, the key insights are fairly simple and
 may be helpful to you in solving your problem sets this week and on the
 exam.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that the discounted value of a stream of payoffs at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 given some domain is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\cdot|t)$
\end_inset

; let the instantaneous payoff be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

; and the discount rate is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Further assume that the relevant domain of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\cdot|t)$
\end_inset

 is the strategy space of all of the players playing the infinite game,
 therefore,
\begin_inset Formula $V:\times_{i\in N}\Sigma_{i}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can use the following recursive equation:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that we could write this as: 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}|t)=u_{i}(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i})+\delta V(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}|t+1)\Rightarrow V=u+\delta V$
\end_inset

 if there are no stochastic elements that would determine the value function
 in the future.
  
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
V(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}|t)=u_{i}(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i})+\delta\mathbb{E}_{t+1}\left[V(\sigma_{i},\sigma_{-i}|t+1)\right]\Rightarrow V=u+\delta\mathbb{E}_{t+1}\left[V\right].\]

\end_inset

The key is understanding that the value function today is the same as the
 expected value function tomorrow.
 Using the terminology of recursive methods: The value function today is
 equal to the instantaneous payoff today and the discounted continuation
 value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Folk Theorem
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is for those interested in repeated games.
 A more thorough exposition can be found in Chris' lecture notes.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
In an infinitely repeated game, assume that there exists a NE with payoff
 (outcome) equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each player 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a finite set.
 Then as the discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, there exists a SPNE with a feasible payoff greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in each period (per-period payoffs) which can be sustained by a minmax
 strategy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the per-period or average payoff, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\pi}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated using the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\bar{\pi}=(1-\delta)\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\delta^{t}u_{t},\]

\end_inset

and the feasible payoffs are a set of convex combination of the pure strategy
 payoffs.
 
\end_layout

